<td>Over 0.25</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Ad-heavy pages often fail LCP because third-party scripts block rendering. Lazy load ads below the fold. Defer non-critical JavaScript. Use <code>fetchpriority="high"</code> on your hero image to tell the browser what to load first.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Core Web Vitals thresholds for news websites" src="/images/blog/news-seo-core-web-vitals.webp" /></p>
<h3>News-Specific XML Sitemaps</h3>
<p>Standard XML sitemaps list your pages. News sitemaps tell Google which articles are recent and time-sensitive. Google requires a separate news sitemap that includes only articles published within the last 48 hours.</p>
<p>Your <a href="/blog/create-xml-sitemap/">XML sitemap</a> setup should include:</p>
<ul>
<li>A standard sitemap for all pages</li>
<li>A news sitemap with articles from the past 48 hours</li>
<li>Publication name, language, and article title in each entry</li>
<li>Automatic removal of articles older than 48 hours</li>
</ul>
<p>Submit both sitemaps in Google Search Console. Monitor the coverage report for indexing errors.</p>
<h3>URL Structure for News Sites</h3>
<p>Clean, descriptive URLs help Google understand article topics before crawling the full page. Use a consistent <a href="/blog/url-structure-seo/">URL structure</a> pattern:</p>
<pre><code>yoursite.com/category/article-slug
yoursite.com/politics/senate-passes-climate-bill-2026
</code></pre>
<p>Avoid query parameters, session IDs, or date-based URL folders that create duplicate content issues. If your CMS generates URLs with <code>/2026/03/30/article-title/</code>, consider whether those date folders add SEO value. For breaking news, they often do not.</p>
<h3>Crawl Budget Management</h3>
<p>A site publishing 200 articles per day generates 6,000 new URLs per month. Add category pages, tag pages, author pages, and pagination pages and the total crawl demand grows to 20,000+ URLs monthly.</p>
<p>Google allocates a crawl budget based on site health and perceived value. If Googlebot wastes crawls on thin tag pages or duplicate pagination URLs, your breaking stories get crawled later.</p>
<p>Prioritize crawl budget with these steps:</p>
<ul>
<li>Block thin tag and archive pages with <a href="/blog/noindex-nofollow-guide/">noindex directives</a></li>
<li>Use canonical tags on syndicated or republished content</li>
<li>Return proper <a href="/blog/http-status-codes-seo/">HTTP status codes</a> for removed articles (410 for permanently deleted)</li>
<li>Monitor crawl stats in Search Console</li>
</ul>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="News site crawl budget allocation diagram" src="/images/blog/news-seo-crawl-budget.webp" /></p>
